const descriptions = {
  "AlmaLinux": "Another RHEL-compatible rebuild, backed by CloudLinux. ABI-compatible with RHEL for enterprise deployments. Strong cloud and hosting provider adoption.",
  "Alpine Linux": "Tiny, security-oriented distro using musl libc and BusyBox. The de facto standard for Docker containers. Extremely minimal — perfect for servers and embedded systems.",
  "antiX": "Systemd-free, ultra-lightweight Debian derivative. Can resurrect hardware from 2004. Uses IceWM window manager and sysvinit/runit. Ideal for ancient PCs with 256 MB RAM.",
  "Arch Linux": "A DIY rolling-release distro. Minimal base install — you build everything from scratch. The AUR provides access to virtually any Linux software. The Arch Wiki is the best documentation in Linux.",
  "Artix Linux": "Arch Linux without systemd. Offers OpenRC, runit, s6, or dinit as init systems. For users who want Arch's rolling packages but reject the systemd ecosystem.",
  "Asahi Linux": "Linux for Apple Silicon Macs (M1/M2/M3/M4). Reverse-engineers Apple's hardware to bring Linux to Mac. Based on Fedora. The only way to run Linux natively on modern Apple hardware.",
  "Aurora": "The KDE Plasma counterpart to Bluefin from the Universal Blue project. Combines an unbreakable read-only Fedora Kinoite core with an outstanding out-of-the-box developer experience.",
  "Bazzite": "Immutable, gaming-focused Fedora variant using rpm-ostree. Pre-configured for Steam, Lutris, and gaming. Available in desktop and HTPC/Steam Deck modes. Atomic updates prevent breakage.",
  "Bluefin": "A developer-focused, ChromeOS-like cloud native image. Based on Fedora Silverblue but loaded with Ubuntu's usability, brew, and container tools. Unbreakable, automated updates.",
  "CachyOS": "Performance-optimized Arch derivative. Compiles packages with x86-64-v3/v4 CPU instructions for measurably faster execution. Custom kernel schedulers for gaming and workloads.",
  "Debian": "The universal operating system. Rock-solid stability, enormous package repository, and the foundation for Ubuntu, Mint, and dozens of others. Conservative release cycle prioritizes reliability.",
  "Deepin": "Chinese distro known for its stunningly beautiful Deepin Desktop Environment. Polished animations and iOS-like design. Based on Debian.",
  "Devuan": "Debian without systemd — a fork created by developers opposed to systemd's scope creep. Uses sysvinit or OpenRC. All the Debian ecosystem without the init system controversy.",
  "Edubuntu": "Ubuntu flavored for education. Ships with educational software, classroom management tools, and a child-friendly interface. Ideal for schools and learning environments.",
  "elementary OS": "A beautifully curated macOS-like experience. The Pantheon desktop is minimal and opinionated — fewer settings, maximum polish. Pay-what-you-want app store.",
  "EndeavourOS": "A terminal-centric Arch-based distro with a graphical installer. Closer to vanilla Arch than Manjaro — minimal modifications, community-focused, great for learning Arch workflows.",
  "Fedora Silverblue": "Immutable variant of Fedora using rpm-ostree. The root filesystem is read-only; apps run in Flatpak or Toolbox containers. Atomic updates with automatic rollback on failure.",
  "Fedora Workstation": "Red Hat's community distro and RHEL proving ground. Ships the latest GNOME, cutting-edge kernels, and Wayland by default. Ideal for developers wanting fresh software on a stable base.",
  "Garuda Linux": "Performance-focused Arch derivative with gaming optimizations, BTRFS snapshots, and a heavily themed KDE desktop. Ships with Chaotic-AUR for pre-compiled AUR packages.",
  "Gentoo": "Source-based meta-distribution. Compile every package from source with USE flags for exact hardware optimization. Maximum control, maximum learning, maximum build time.",
  "Kali Linux": "The industry standard for penetration testing and security auditing. Packed with hundreds of offensive security tools. Maintained by Offensive Security. Not for daily desktop use.",
  "Kubuntu": "Ubuntu with KDE Plasma instead of GNOME. Highly customizable interface with widgets, panels, and deep theming. Same Ubuntu base and repos.",
  "Linux Mint": "A user-friendly distro based on Ubuntu with a traditional Cinnamon desktop. Ships without Snaps, uses Flatpak. Ideal for Windows migrants wanting a familiar taskbar-and-menu interface.",
  "Lubuntu": "The lightest official Ubuntu flavor, using LXQt. Can run on machines with as little as 1 GB RAM. Ideal for aging hardware.",
  "Manjaro": "User-friendly Arch derivative with delayed rolling updates for extra stability. Ships with a graphical installer and pre-configured DEs. Access to AUR without the Arch learning curve.",
  "MX Linux": "Midweight Debian-based distro with excellent MX Tools suite. Can use sysvinit instead of systemd. Top DistroWatch ranking for years. Great for older hardware.",
  "NixOS": "Declarative, reproducible OS. Your entire system is defined in a single configuration file. Atomic upgrades and rollbacks. Multiple package versions can coexist. Revolutionary but steep learning curve.",
  "Nobara Linux": "Gaming-optimized Fedora fork by a Proton-GE developer. Includes custom kernel patches, CPU schedulers, and pre-configured NVIDIA drivers for maximum gaming performance.",
  "OpenMediaVault": "Lightweight Debian-based NAS solution. Simpler than TrueNAS, ideal for Raspberry Pi or repurposed hardware. Plugin-based, manages Docker, SMB, NFS shares via web UI.",
  "openSUSE Leap": "Fixed-release counterpart to Tumbleweed, sharing code with SUSE Linux Enterprise. Excellent for workstations and home servers needing stability with YaST management.",
  "openSUSE Tumbleweed": "Pure rolling-release distro with automated openQA testing for every snapshot. Offers YaST — the most powerful graphical system configuration tool in Linux. Strong KDE integration.",
  "OpenWrt": "Custom Linux firmware for routers and networking devices. Turns consumer routers into powerful, configurable network appliances with firewall, VPN, QoS, and advanced routing.",
  "Parrot OS": "Debian-based security distro. Offers both a Security edition (pentesting) and a Home edition (privacy desktop). More desktop-friendly than Kali with cloud pentesting focus.",
  "Pop!_OS": "System76's Ubuntu-based distro with excellent NVIDIA driver support, a tiling-capable GNOME desktop, and developer-friendly tools. Great for gaming and development on NVIDIA hardware.",
  "Proxmox VE": "Enterprise virtualization platform based on Debian. Manages KVM VMs and LXC containers via web interface. Free with optional paid support. The open-source alternative to VMware ESXi.",
  "Puppy Linux": "Ultra-lightweight distro that loads entirely into RAM. Can run on machines from the early 2000s with 256 MB RAM. Boots from USB/CD. Unique save-file persistence model.",
  "Qubes OS": "Security-by-compartmentalization OS using Xen hypervisor. Every app runs in an isolated VM. Endorsed by Edward Snowden. The most secure desktop OS available — at the cost of complexity and RAM.",
  "Raspberry Pi OS": "The official OS for Raspberry Pi SBCs. Debian-based, optimized for ARM. Pre-configured with GPIO libraries, Python, and education tools. The go-to for Raspberry Pi projects.",
  "Rocky Linux": "Community-driven RHEL rebuild. 1:1 binary compatible with RHEL, providing 10-year enterprise support for free. Created to replace CentOS as the go-to free enterprise server OS.",
  "Slackware": "The oldest active Linux distro (since 1993). No dependency resolution — packages are simple tarballs. Maximum simplicity and Unix philosophy. A rite of passage for Linux enthusiasts.",
  "Solus": "Independent curated rolling-release distro. Home of the Budgie desktop. Focuses on desktop computing excellence — not servers, not enterprise, just a beautiful desktop experience.",
  "SteamOS": "Valve's immutable Arch-based OS powering the Steam Deck. Console-like gaming experience with Gamescope compositor. Designed for HTPC and controller-driven gaming.",
  "Tails": "The Amnesic Incognito Live System. Boots from USB, routes everything through Tor, wipes all data on shutdown. Used by journalists and activists under surveillance. Ephemeral by design.",
  "Trisquel": "FSF-endorsed, 100% free/libre Ubuntu derivative. Ships zero proprietary software, firmware, or drivers. For users who demand absolute software freedom, even at the cost of hardware support.",
  "TrueNAS SCALE": "Enterprise-grade open-source NAS platform. Linux-based (Debian) with ZFS, Docker, and VM support via web interface. The standard for home and business network storage.",
  "Ubuntu": "The most popular desktop Linux distro. Ubuntu prioritizes ease of use with a polished GNOME desktop, Snap integration, and 5-year LTS support. Excellent hardware compatibility and massive community.",
  "Ubuntu Studio": "Ubuntu configured for content creators. Ships with a low-latency kernel, JACK audio, Ardour, Kdenlive, GIMP, and Blender pre-installed. Real-time audio production ready out of box.",
  "Vanilla OS": "Next-gen immutable distro using the apx/abroot system. Atomic updates, Distrobox integration for running packages from any distro. Ubuntu/Debian base with a unique hybrid package approach.",
  "Void Linux": "Independent rolling-release distro using runit (not systemd) and XBPS package manager. Available with glibc or musl C library. Clean, fast, and opinionated.",
  "Whonix": "Privacy-focused distro running inside VMs. All traffic is forced through Tor via a separate Gateway VM, making IP leaks architecturally impossible. More persistent than Tails.",
  "Xubuntu": "Ubuntu with the lightweight Xfce desktop. Good balance of features and performance for older or mid-range hardware.",
  "Zorin OS": "Designed to look and feel like Windows or macOS. Beautiful layout options make the transition from other OS seamless. Based on Ubuntu LTS."
};

